Summary Statistics

Mean and Standard Deviation

Mean:

  • Measure of central tendency
  • Average of all observations for a given variable

Standard Deviation:

  • Measure of variability or “spread” of data
  • Square root of the sum of the squared deviations from the mean
  • (Don’t worry too much about these specifics; you won’t need to calculate SDs in this exercise)

Inferential Statistics

Normal Distribution

The normal distribution is a very common probability distribution

  • Also known as a Gaussian distribution or “bell curve”
  • Many variables are normally distributed (e.g., height, weight, IQ)
  • We can use it to make inferences about unknown variables

Inferential Statistics

Normal Distribution

Any normal distribution can be described by two parameters:

  • The mean indicates where the peak of the distribution is located
  • The standard deviation indicates the typical distance between any given point and the mean

Inferential Statistics

z-Scores

A z-score indicates the number of standard deviations between a particular observation and the mean.

\[z = \frac{value - mean}{SD}\]

Big Five Inventory

John, Donahue, & Kentle, 1991

  • Extraversion: assertive, full of energy, talkative
  • Agreeableness: sympathetic, affectionate, kind
  • Conscientiousness: planful, thorough, organized
  • Neuroticism: anxious, tense
  • Openness to experience: curious, imaginative, interested in a range of topics

Big Five Inventory: Extraversion

  • Mean: 3.31
  • SD: 0.76

Big Five Inventory: Agreeableness

  • Mean: 3.87
  • SD: 0.7

Big Five Inventory: Conscientiousness

  • SD: 0.69

Big Five Inventory: Neuroticism

  • SD: 0.57

Big Five Inventory: Opennness to Experience

Regulatory Focus Questionnaire

Higgins et al., 2001

  • Prevention pride: historical success in maintaining security and fulfilling responsibilities; approach new goals vigilantly
  • Promotion pride: historical success in achieving hopes and aspirations; approach new goals eagerly

Regulatory Focus Questionnaire

Higgins et al., 2001

  • Prevention Mean: 4.08 (SD = 0.73)
  • Promotion Mean: 3.98 (SD = 0.48)

Regulatory Mode Questionnaire

Kruglanski et al., 2000

  • Assessment: oriented toward thinking and critical evaluation in goal pursuit
  • Locomotion: oriented toward doing, movement, and action in goal pursuit

Regulatory Mode Questionnaire

Kruglanski et al., 2000

  • Assessment Mean: 4.17 (SD = 0.93)
  • Locomotion Mean: 4.16 (SD = 0.74)

Moral Foundations Questionnaire

Graham, Haidt, & Nosek, 2008

  • Care/Harm: kindness, compassion, nurturance
  • Fairness/Cheating: justice, equality
  • Loyalty/Betrayal: patriotism, ingroup loyalty
  • Authority/Subversion: authority, respect for traditions
  • Sanctity/Degradation: purity, chastity, avoidance of disgusting behavior

Moral Foundations Questionnaire

Graham, Haidt, & Nosek, 2008

  • Care/Harm Mean: 23.1 (SD = 3.9)
  • Fairness/Cheating Mean: 21.8 (SD = 3.39)
  • Loyalty/Betrayal Mean: 14.9 (SD = 5.17)
  • Authority/Subversion Mean: 16.9 (SD = 5.22)
  • Sanctity/Degradation Mean: 16.4 (SD = 6.2)

Relationship Theories Questionnaire

Franiuk, Cohen, & Pomerantz, 2002

  • Soulmate theories: relationship satisfaction depends upon finding the right person
  • Work-it-out theories: relationship satisfaction depends upon putting effort into the relationship

Relationship Theories Questionnaire

Franiuk, Cohen, & Pomerantz, 2002

  • Soulmate Mean: 4.37 (SD = 0.68)
  • Work-It-Out Mean: 4.22 (SD = 1.26)

Aspiration Index

Kasser & Ryan, 1996

  • Intrinsic: fulfill fundamental needs
    • Self-acceptance
    • Affiliation
    • Feeling that one is part of a community
    • Physical fitness
  • Extrinsic: means to some other end
    • Financial success
    • Attractive appearance
    • Social recognition

Aspiration Index

Kasser & Ryan, 1996

  • Self-Acceptance: 0.95
  • Affiliation: 0.92
  • Community Feeling: 0.04
  • Physical Fitness: 0.92
  • Financial Success: -0.27
  • Attractive Appearance: -0.88
  • Social Recognition: -1.68
